(A Day in the Life, Super Size Me) in a short video about choice, technology, and how to know which possibility to go after:
Isn’t this true with some of the Social Media choices we face? With so many choices – which do you go after? Certainly not all of them – that would turn into a slow process of none of them.
Hate Facebook but love Pinterest? Go with Pinterest first.
Go after the one that thrills you first!
When it comes to which Social Media track (or
) to go after first, what gives you the chills or thrills?
. Lots of great thinking going on.
Stop Stealing Dreams [Video & eBook] from Seth Godin
Conversation Conductor & Social Mediatician: Amplify Reach, Relationships, and Revenues for Small, Rural and Independent Business. Blogging & Social Media as Conversation Stations.
Do you think that it’s possible to focus on one social media channel and do great – than focusing on lots but look so mediocre that it scares people away?

Great question:-) I think the probability of success increases – especially if just starting out – when one focuses on a single channel, and preferably the channel or network they like or use most. So in that way, yes – one focused success is better than widespread mediocrity.

Additionally, I think once thriving in a single network, it’s wise to branch out to extend voice, reach, or presence. I also think curiosity to see if success can be replicated motivates us to try other channels.
Stations, I coach small business and
solopreneurs to use Blogs and Social Media to amplify their reach, their relationships, and their revenues.
